# Product Ops Rules (AI Product Development)

## 1) Outcome-first rule
- Tie every artifact to one primary customer/business outcome metric.
- Do not proceed with solution detail if the outcome is unclear.

## 2) Evidence integrity rule
- Distinguish clearly between:
  - evidence (observed facts),
  - assumptions (untested beliefs),
  - recommendations (proposed actions).
- Never invent customer quotes, data points, or sources.

## 3) Continuous discovery rule
- For active initiatives, include recent customer evidence (ideally last 14 days).
- If evidence is stale, recommend discovery actions before committing major scope.

## 4) Experimentation rule
- For high-risk assumptions, produce an experiment card before finalizing PRD scope.
- Define success/failure thresholds and guardrails.

## 5) Responsible AI rule
- Flag privacy, bias, misuse, and transparency risks for AI-enabled capabilities.
- Recommend human review checkpoints for high-impact decisions.

## 6) Artifact quality rule
- Use concise, structured headings.
- Use clear owners, dates, and next actions.
- Include explicit "out of scope" where relevant.

## 7) Decision clarity rule
- End major docs with decision recommendation:
  - continue, iterate, pause, or stop;
  - owner and date for decision.

## 8) Collaboration rule
- Ensure product, design/research, and engineering viewpoints are represented.
- Highlight unresolved cross-functional tradeoffs.

## 9) Design system reuse rule
- For UI work, check existing design system patterns/components before creating new ones.
- If proposing a new component, document:
  - why existing components do not fit,
  - expected reuse potential,
  - ownership for maintenance.

## 10) Show-your-work rule
- For major proposals, include evidence links, assumption list, and tradeoff rationale.
- Do not rely on polished prototypes as proof of problem-solution fit.

## 11) Discovery-before-delivery rule
- Do not fast-track to implementation when problem framing is weak.
- Require at least one explicit assumption test for high-uncertainty initiatives.
